  "original_title": "\u0d9c\u0dca\u200d\u0dbb\u0dc4\u0dbd\u0ddd\u0d9a \u0db4\u0dc4\u0d9a\u0dca \u0dc4\u0dd9\u0da7 \u0d85\u0dbd\u0dd4\u0dba\u0db8 \u0d91\u0d9a\u0db8 \u0dbb\u0dda\u0d9b\u0dcf\u0dc0\u0d9a",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Five planets in the same line tomorrow morning",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "It is possible to see the five planets belonging to the solar system in the same line these days and that phenomenon will be better seen from 4.40 am tomorrow (29) until sunrise tomorrow, says the lecturer at the Planetarium Geethanjana Wanigasekara.",
        "He noted that the planets Mercury, Venus, Mars, Jupiter and Saturn were observed in the sky at the same time, and that the effect of the moon's light was less visible this morning.",
        "Mr. Wanigasekara said that although it is difficult to identify Saturn, which is located slightly above the sky, Venus and Jupiter can be seen very brightly and other planets can also be identified by connecting those planets with the mind.",
        "He added that this opportunity could be seen until the first week of July.",
        "Thus, the five planets will be seen in the same line again in the year 2040."
      ],
